00:05:31.770 --> 00:05:36.060
VRSA is just vancomycin
resistant MRSA, right?

00:05:36.060 --> 00:05:38.920 position:56%
And vancomycin is a crappy drug, but
this is the one we're really afraid

00:05:38.920 --> 00:05:41.680
of because that's the
last drug we've got.

00:05:41.680 --> 00:05:44.410
VRA, CRA, these are just
different monikers for superbugs.

00:05:44.410 --> 00:05:47.350
And these are just basically
disease-causing bacteria

00:05:47.350 --> 00:05:51.830
that are resistant to antibiotics,
usually multiple antibiotics,

00:05:51.830 --> 00:05:55.050
although we usually refer
to them based on one drug.

00:05:55.050 --> 00:05:57.810
And so people ask me
all the time, you know,

00:05:57.810 --> 00:06:00.510
"So how does this bacterium
-- " that's a bacterium to me,

00:06:00.510 --> 00:06:02.530
"how does a bacterium turn
into a super-bacterium?"

00:06:02.530 --> 00:06:04.520
And that's a super bacteria to me.

00:06:04.520 --> 00:06:05.910
"How does it go from this to this?"

00:06:05.910 --> 00:06:09.960
And it goes from this to
this by changes in the DNA.

00:06:09.960 --> 00:06:14.560
So bacteria multiply themselves,
so they don't reproduce sexually;

00:06:14.560 --> 00:06:18.990 position:56%
they just make copies of their DNA,
and then they split from one to two,

00:06:18.990 --> 00:06:21.720
and the two become
four, eight, 16, 32.

00:06:21.720 --> 00:06:24.040
And each time they do that,
they have to make copies

00:06:24.040 --> 00:06:29.130
of four-and-a-half, sometimes,
you know, more millions of bases.

00:06:29.130 --> 00:06:33.670
So two, to four, to five million
bases of DNA, Gs, As, Ts, and Cs.

00:06:33.670 --> 00:06:36.750
And when they do that, they
can make errors and some

00:06:36.750 --> 00:06:39.500
of those errors result
in changes in proteins

00:06:39.500 --> 00:06:42.380
that make them resistant
to antibiotics.

00:06:42.380 --> 00:06:45.070
So the other thing that they
can do is some bacteria carry

00:06:45.070 --> 00:06:48.770
around these extra little
packages of DNA called "plasmids,"

00:06:48.770 --> 00:06:52.610
or other elements, and they can
pass these to other bacteria.

00:06:52.610 --> 00:06:56.740
So in a single genetic event,
they can pass resistance to six,

00:06:56.740 --> 00:06:58.800
seven different antibiotics just

00:06:58.800 --> 00:07:02.800
by bumping together
and passing this DNA.

00:07:02.800 --> 00:07:05.010
And now what we have
is we have a world war.

00:07:05.010 --> 00:07:07.170
We have bacteria that
are already carrying lots

00:07:07.170 --> 00:07:10.360
of different resistance genes,
and they're just waiting

00:07:10.360 --> 00:07:14.460
for that one last resistance gene
to get that royal flush, right?

00:07:14.460 --> 00:07:18.060 position:56%
And this is what we're really afraid
of, right, we have lots of bacteria

00:07:18.060 --> 00:07:20.700
that are one card away
from a royal flush.

00:07:20.700 --> 00:07:23.440
And now we know that that last
card is floating around out there.

00:07:23.440 --> 00:07:25.330
I'm going to come back
to this later.

00:07:25.330 --> 00:07:29.440
So that's happening all
the time in the background,

00:07:29.440 --> 00:07:31.220
but most of the time,
that's a dead end.

00:07:31.220 --> 00:07:35.720
Right; so these mutations happen,
and then those bacteria fizzle out.

00:07:35.720 --> 00:07:38.500 position:56%
But if you're in an environment
where there are lots of antibiotics,

00:07:38.500 --> 00:07:41.940
even one of those mutations
can result

00:07:41.940 --> 00:07:45.100
in a rapid evolution
drug resistant bacteria.

00:07:45.100 --> 00:07:48.440
So in an environment where
you have lots of drugs,

00:07:48.440 --> 00:07:50.640
then the susceptible
bacteria die off --

00:07:50.640 --> 00:07:52.830
excuse my sort of South
Park style cartoons,

00:07:52.830 --> 00:07:54.670
but these are the best I can draw,

00:07:54.670 --> 00:07:58.070
and that resistant one
then goes on to multiply.

00:07:58.070 --> 00:08:02.150
So one becomes two -- I skipped
a step, two becomes four,

00:08:02.150 --> 00:08:03.890
four becomes eight, et cetera.

00:08:03.890 --> 00:08:06.120
And you can go from a single cell

00:08:06.120 --> 00:08:09.920
to a billion drug-resistant
bacteria in 24 hours.

00:08:09.920 --> 00:08:14.050
So E. Coli can double, can do
these doubling every 30 minutes.

00:08:14.050 --> 00:08:17.100
And E. Coli is one of the worst
superbugs that we deal with today.

00:08:17.100 --> 00:08:22.130 position:56%
So you can go from a single superbug
cell to billions in 24 hours.

00:08:22.130 --> 00:08:25.710
So there's a lot of confusion
in the mainstream media.

00:08:25.710 --> 00:08:28.760
You all are brilliant, so I
probably don't need to say this.

00:08:28.760 --> 00:08:33.140
But, you know, the media talks
about people becoming resistant

00:08:33.140 --> 00:08:35.450
to antibiotics, but I think it's
really important to make sure

00:08:35.450 --> 00:08:38.090
that you understand this, even
though it's a simple concept,

00:08:38.090 --> 00:08:40.140
that it's not people that
are becoming resistant

00:08:40.140 --> 00:08:42.030
to antibiotics, it's bacteria.

00:08:42.030 --> 00:08:44.560
And those are colonizing
us and infecting us,

00:08:44.560 --> 00:08:47.000
and those infections
are harder to treat,

00:08:47.000 --> 00:08:51.210
it gives doctors fewer choices,
and these result in more

00:08:51.210 --> 00:08:52.550
and more deaths every year.

00:08:52.550 --> 00:08:55.560
And the CDC conservatively
estimates today

00:08:55.560 --> 00:08:59.580
that 23,000 Americans die
each year of superbugs.

00:08:59.580 --> 00:09:03.240
And Tom Frieden, the head of the
CDC underscored several times

00:09:03.240 --> 00:09:05.000
that this was a conservative
