this argument for 40 years.

00:17:33.730 --> 00:17:36.240
But for years the argument
was framed

00:17:36.240 --> 00:17:38.320
around the classic
food-borne pathogens

00:17:38.320 --> 00:17:40.250
like salmonella and campylobacter.

00:17:40.250 --> 00:17:43.030
I'm sure you've all
heard of salmonella.

00:17:43.030 --> 00:17:45.520
Have you heard of campylobacter?

00:17:45.520 --> 00:17:49.280
Okay; it turns out that they
are sort of tied number one

00:17:49.280 --> 00:17:52.320
and number two in terms
of causing diarrhea

00:17:52.320 --> 00:17:55.760
in the United States,
bacterial diarrhea.

00:17:55.760 --> 00:18:01.650
And together they cause
about 2.6 million cases

00:18:01.650 --> 00:18:03.860
of diarrhea, all right?

00:18:03.860 --> 00:18:07.910
And most of that is coming from
contaminated poultry products.

00:18:07.910 --> 00:18:12.030
And the CDC estimates
that about 410,000

00:18:12.030 --> 00:18:14.090
of these infections are
antibiotic-resistant.

00:18:14.090 --> 00:18:17.290
And that resistance can be traced
back to either contemporary

00:18:17.290 --> 00:18:20.090
or historic use of antibiotics
in food animal production.

00:18:20.090 --> 00:18:22.270
So just to put things in
perspective, that's the population

00:18:22.270 --> 00:18:25.590
of Miami getting drug-resistant
food borne infections

00:18:25.590 --> 00:18:28.250
in the United States each year.

00:18:28.250 --> 00:18:32.030
But not very many people
die of those infections.

00:18:32.030 --> 00:18:35.360
So most people who get
diarrhea will have, you know,

00:18:35.360 --> 00:18:38.420
they'll be uncomfortable for five
or six days, they'll use a lot

00:18:38.420 --> 00:18:39.720
of toilet paper, and
they'll recover.

00:18:39.720 --> 00:18:42.780
A thousand people will
not; they die.

00:18:42.780 --> 00:18:44.360 position:56%
It gets into the blood and they die.

00:18:44.360 --> 00:18:47.590
But apparently, a thousand
people is not enough

00:18:47.590 --> 00:18:51.060
to change policy in
the United States.

00:18:51.060 --> 00:18:53.990
So we have to move --
I've been saying for years

00:18:53.990 --> 00:18:55.330
that we have to move back.

00:18:55.330 --> 00:18:58.230
We need to move beyond the
classic food borne pathogens,

00:18:58.230 --> 00:18:59.980
because there's a lot
more than salmonella

00:18:59.980 --> 00:19:02.050
and campylobacter in
the food supply.

00:19:02.050 --> 00:19:03.870
We need to understand the --

00:19:03.870 --> 00:19:08.000
what we call the "colonizing
opportunist pathogens," or COPs.

00:19:08.000 --> 00:19:09.300
These are the big killers.

00:19:09.300 --> 00:19:11.760
And when you talk to an
infectious disease doc,

00:19:11.760 --> 00:19:13.610
they want to know about these guys.

00:19:13.610 --> 00:19:15.520
They don't care about
salmonella and campylobacter;

00:19:15.520 --> 00:19:17.560
they just don't kill enough people.

00:19:17.560 --> 00:19:19.800
So we're not talking
about Andy Griffith there.

00:19:19.800 --> 00:19:22.280
We're talking more along the
lines of Harvey Keitel in the

00:19:22.280 --> 00:19:24.190
"Bad Lieutenant," you know.

00:19:24.190 --> 00:19:28.090
Some of these movie posters really
give it all away, right, "Gambler,

00:19:28.090 --> 00:19:29.910
Thief, Junkie, Killer, Cop."

00:19:29.910 --> 00:19:33.300
All right; anyway it's
colonizing opportunist pathogens.

00:19:33.300 --> 00:19:35.760
These include things like E. Coli,

00:19:35.760 --> 00:19:38.100
escherichia intestinal
pathogenic E. Coli,

00:19:38.100 --> 00:19:40.390
the kind that causes
bladder infections.

00:19:40.390 --> 00:19:42.930
Klebsiella pneumonia; have
you ever heard of KLEB,

00:19:42.930 --> 00:19:44.810
klebsiella, a few of you.

00:19:44.810 --> 00:19:46.540
So this is a big killer
in the United States.

00:19:46.540 --> 00:19:48.580
One of the biggest
superbugs is that klebsiella.

00:19:48.580 --> 00:19:50.770
And one of the biggest
superbugs is in E. Coli.

00:19:50.770 --> 00:19:55.160
And one of the biggest superbugs
is staph aureus, M R S A, MRSA.

00:19:55.160 --> 00:19:58.820
So COPs can live in
or on our bodies.

00:19:58.820 --> 00:20:01.580
So staph can live in your
nose, in your throat,

00:20:01.580 --> 00:20:04.120
for years without you knowing it.

00:20:04.120 --> 00:20:05.420
No symptoms.

00:20:05.420 --> 00:20:07.850
You can just be a carrier, and you
can share it with other people.

00:20:07.850 --> 00:20:10.820
E. Coli can live in
your gut for decades

00:20:10.820 --> 00:20:12.870
and you wouldn't even know it.

00:20:12.870 --> 00:20:15.050
It doesn't cause symptoms
until it gets into the bladder,

00:20:15.050 --> 00:20:17.670
until it gets into the blood.

00:20:17.670 --> 00:20:19.240
And so you can become
this reservoir.

00:20:19.240 --> 00:20:23.030
And so these COPs cause what I
like to call "insidious epidemics."

00:20:23.030 --> 00:20:24.740
So they can spread globally.

00:20:24.740 --> 00:20:26.040
They can get on planes with us.

00:20:26.040 --> 00:20:29.500
They get on trains and
boats, and they get on meat,

00:20:29.500 --> 00:20:31.170
and they travel the world.

00:20:31.170 --> 00:20:35.170
The problem is that they have
asymptomatic colonization.

00:20:35.170 --> 00:20:37.970
So these fever monitors in airports
are not going to work, right,

00:20:37.970 --> 00:20:39.720
