00:25:41.080 --> 00:25:44.220
So a few years ago,
we decided we wanted

00:25:44.220 --> 00:25:46.560
to understand the origins
of pig MRSA.

00:25:46.560 --> 00:25:52.550
So we collected MRSA strains as
MRSA -- this is sequence type 398.

00:25:52.550 --> 00:25:56.860
This is just a geeky label that
people like me put on bacteria.

00:25:56.860 --> 00:25:59.240
I'll talk more about
sequence types later.

00:25:59.240 --> 00:26:04.820
But we collected all these, and
we collected them from people,

00:26:04.820 --> 00:26:08.130
and from animals, and
those that were M R S A,

00:26:08.130 --> 00:26:12.120
and those that were
susceptible to Methicillin,

00:26:12.120 --> 00:26:14.530
and we sequenced the genomes
of nearly a hundred of these.

00:26:14.530 --> 00:26:17.120
And then we drew an
evolutionary tree

00:26:17.120 --> 00:26:20.000
to understand how they were
related to one another.

00:26:20.000 --> 00:26:21.720
And so this was the tree.

00:26:21.720 --> 00:26:25.120
I don't expect you guys
to really memorize this,

00:26:25.120 --> 00:26:29.070
but each of these nodes -- sorry,
each of these little names,

00:26:29.070 --> 00:26:31.690
the little digits at the
end is a little islet,

00:26:31.690 --> 00:26:34.080
that is a different staph bacteria.

00:26:34.080 --> 00:26:37.240
And then pink is from people --

00:26:37.240 --> 00:26:42.550
sorry pink is from animals,
and gray is from people.

00:26:42.550 --> 00:26:44.770
And you see that the pink
are all clustered up there.

00:26:44.770 --> 00:26:47.480
It turns out that that's
the livestock lineage,

00:26:47.480 --> 00:26:49.860
and these down here
are the older ones,

00:26:49.860 --> 00:26:52.010
those are the livestock
independent lineages.

00:26:52.010 --> 00:26:53.830
Those are the ones of people.

00:26:53.830 --> 00:26:57.110
And so what we learned
from doing this was

00:26:57.110 --> 00:26:58.590
that the livestock associated

00:26:58.590 --> 00:27:02.750
with MRSA actually evolved
from staph and people.

00:27:02.750 --> 00:27:04.050
So I have a cartoon version.

00:27:04.050 --> 00:27:05.350
I think this is better.

00:27:05.350 --> 00:27:06.960
Right; so Fisher-Price
is better even

00:27:06.960 --> 00:27:08.660
for Nobel laureates,
they've told me.

00:27:08.660 --> 00:27:13.210
All right; so it turns out we
have staph circulating in people.

00:27:13.210 --> 00:27:17.750
Those people inadvertently
pass staph to the animals.

00:27:17.750 --> 00:27:20.410
So -- well this is kind
of gross, but, you know,

00:27:20.410 --> 00:27:24.060
farmer blow snot rockets.

00:27:24.060 --> 00:27:26.160
Anyway, you can share
bacteria with your animals

00:27:26.160 --> 00:27:27.550
from your nose, possibly.

00:27:27.550 --> 00:27:32.570
And then where we're using
lots of antibiotics in animals,

00:27:32.570 --> 00:27:38.660 position:56%
we get this transition from M S S
A, so susceptible, to M R S A, MRSA.

00:27:38.660 --> 00:27:41.630
And then that's spreading
now to back to people.

00:27:41.630 --> 00:27:43.700
And this is a very
clear -- we have --

00:27:43.700 --> 00:27:47.430
this epidemiology is very clear
now that this is happening.

00:27:47.430 --> 00:27:49.300
What's also happening, and
I mentioned this before,

00:27:49.300 --> 00:27:52.310
is that the people living with
these people are at very high risk

00:27:52.310 --> 00:27:54.670
for picking these up as well.

00:27:54.670 --> 00:27:56.300
But the story continues to evolve.

00:27:56.300 --> 00:27:59.650
So we're studying this very
intensely in Northern Europe

00:27:59.650 --> 00:28:03.780 position:56%
where we have access to the animals,
to drug records, to everything,

00:28:03.780 --> 00:28:05.910
whereas in the United States,
we get a shotgun in our face

00:28:05.910 --> 00:28:07.570
when we try to go onto these farms.

00:28:07.570 --> 00:28:09.720
But there we can study
these very clearly.

00:28:09.720 --> 00:28:13.440
And we see now it's spilling
over into the general community.

00:28:13.440 --> 00:28:17.570
It's usually the people
living near these farm workers

00:28:17.570 --> 00:28:20.610
or around the farm, so it could
be environmental exposures,

00:28:20.610 --> 00:28:24.000
or it could be secondary
exposure to these people.

00:28:24.000 --> 00:28:25.710
We've seen outbreaks in hospitals

00:28:25.710 --> 00:28:28.200
that are clearly the
livestock strains.

00:28:28.200 --> 00:28:31.860 position:56%
And it's from these people going
into the hospital and then a mistake

00:28:31.860 --> 00:28:35.430 position:56%
with the hand hygiene, probably, and
they pass it onto other patients.

00:28:35.430 --> 00:28:38.230
And then we now we see
for the first time,

00:28:38.230 --> 00:28:43.250 position:56%
we just published this two weeks ago
in the Clinical Infectious Diseases,

00:28:43.250 --> 00:28:46.590
a really important journal in
my field that there's evidence

00:28:46.590 --> 00:28:48.030
of food-borne transmission too.

00:28:48.030 --> 00:28:50.500
And this is this first
time that we've seen this.

00:28:50.500 --> 00:28:54.010
So this is continuing to evolve.

00:28:54.010 --> 00:28:56.900
We see that the DNA of
these bacteria are changing,

00:28:56.900 --> 00:29:01.360
and they appear to becoming -- some
strains are becoming adapted back

00:29:01.360 --> 00:29:04.920
to humans, and so they could
spread better among humans.

00:29:04.920 --> 00:29:06.380
And so we're keeping
our eye on this,

00:29:06.380 --> 00:29:11.060
and we're using these DNA
technologies to keep watching it.

00:29:11.060 --> 00:29:13.300
It's now become a textbook
example, though.

00:29:13.300 --> 00:29:16.750
So this is just my little
cue to remind me to say this.

00:29:16.750 --> 00:29:20.580
This is a textbook example of what
happens when you use antibiotics

00:29:20.580 --> 00:29:23.710
in the livestock production,
what can happen to people.

00:29:23.710 --> 00:29:27.310
And so when I went to -- I spoke
at the CDC back in January,

00:29:27.310 --> 00:29:32.010 position:56%
and I was just, you know, going over
my slides and I put this slide in.

00:29:32.010 --> 00:29:35.080
And I said, "I should just
double-check that they still have

00:29:35.080 --> 00:29:36.840
that up on their website."

00:29:36.840 --> 00:29:40.510
And I went there and they'd
modified it and they added this.

00:29:40.510 --> 00:29:44.250
So they added, "And areas where
animal handling is common,

00:29:44.250 --> 00:29:46.440
such as a veterinary clinics
and livestock settings."

00:29:46.440 --> 00:29:50.560
So they saw our paper, I guess,
and many, many other papers coming

00:29:50.560 --> 00:29:53.460
out on livestock associated MRSA,
and they modified their website.

00:29:53.460 --> 00:29:56.540
The CDC is -- these
are real scientists,

00:29:56.540 --> 00:30:00.420
and they are an amazing group
of people really looking

00:30:00.420 --> 00:30:03.560
out for our health, and I
thought this was very cool.

00:30:03.560 --> 00:30:06.870
Okay; I'm switching to E. Coli now.

00:30:06.870 --> 00:30:11.010
So staph is the one that lives
on our skin and our noses.

00:30:11.010 --> 00:30:12.770
E. Coli lives in your gut.

00:30:12.770 --> 00:30:14.890
And E. Coli has a lot
of personalities.

00:30:14.890 --> 00:30:17.550
Right; there are thousands
of strains of E. Coli.

00:30:17.550 --> 00:30:19.670
But from a clinical
perspective, there's three;

00:30:19.670 --> 00:30:21.690
there's the good, the
bad, and the ugly.

00:30:21.690 --> 00:30:26.770
So the good is the kind that about
30% of us carry in our gut now.

00:30:26.770 --> 00:30:28.370
It's just part of our microbiome,

00:30:28.370 --> 00:30:31.100
probably just helping
us with digestion.

00:30:31.100 --> 00:30:34.290
The bad is the kind that like
the Jack-in-the-box E. Coli

00:30:34.290 --> 00:30:37.970 position:56%
from the early '90s, right, so
these dramatic food borne outbreaks.

00:30:40.520 --> 00:30:44.000
Jack-in-the-Box responded very well
and helped have something called

00:30:44.000 --> 00:30:47.410
"HACP, which is "hazard
analysis and control points."

00:30:47.410 --> 00:30:51.180
So this really revolutionized
food safety in the United States.

00:30:51.180 --> 00:30:54.740
But we still have these
outbreaks of the bad E. Coli,

00:30:54.740 --> 00:30:56.310
the diarrhea-causing E. Coli.

00:30:56.310 --> 00:30:57.970
And about 52 to 100 people die

00:30:57.970 --> 00:31:00.200
of that E. Coli each year
in the United States.

00:31:00.200 --> 00:31:03.070
But the ugly, the really, really
bad one, or super-bad as I

00:31:03.070 --> 00:31:05.500
like to say sometimes, is the kind

00:31:05.500 --> 00:31:07.480
that causes urinary
tract infections.

00:31:07.480 --> 00:31:09.680
And this one kills about 36,000

00:31:09.680 --> 00:31:12.100
or 40,000 people each
year in the United States.

00:31:12.100 --> 00:31:14.780
So let me tell you a
little bit about expac,

00:31:14.780 --> 00:31:16.930 position:56%
extra-intestinal pathogenic E. Coli.

00:31:16.930 --> 00:31:19.040
Has special features; it
has attachment factors.

00:31:19.040 --> 00:31:20.890
It has these little
hooks on its surfaces

00:31:20.890 --> 00:31:22.880
to attach to your urethral cells.

00:31:22.880 --> 00:31:24.660
It can cloak itself
from the immune system.

00:31:24.660 --> 00:31:26.890
So it can hide itself
from the immune cells

00:31:26.890 --> 00:31:28.210
that want to gobble it up.

00:31:28.210 --> 00:31:29.510
It can produce toxins.

00:31:29.510 --> 00:31:30.970
It can acquire iron.

00:31:30.970 --> 00:31:32.270
It can survive.

00:31:32.270 --> 00:31:33.570
It can deal with uric acid.

00:31:33.570 --> 00:31:37.700
So it can deal with the harsh
environment of the bladder.

00:31:37.700 --> 00:31:40.890
And it causes six to eight
million bladder infections

00:31:40.890 --> 00:31:42.400
in the United States each year,

00:31:42.400 --> 00:31:44.660
a quarter million kidney
infections, at least.

00:31:44.660 --> 00:31:47.910
I think this is an underestimate,
and these numbers are getting old.

00:31:47.910 --> 00:31:50.390
These are 2006 numbers.

00:31:50.390 --> 00:31:52.900
And also deadly blood infections.

00:31:52.900 --> 00:31:57.400
So as I said before, about
36,000 to 40,000 deaths in 2006.

00:31:57.400 --> 00:32:00.660
The number's almost
certainly higher today.

00:32:00.660 --> 00:32:03.930 position:56%
And antibiotics are critical to
prevent this ascent from the bladder

00:32:03.930 --> 00:32:08.850
into the kidneys, and then into
the blood where it kills you.

00:32:08.850 --> 00:32:11.190
And so antibiotic resistance
is a major challenge

00:32:11.190 --> 00:32:12.920
when it comes to expac.

00:32:12.920 --> 00:32:15.940
So I want to lock in
this relationship,

00:32:15.940 --> 00:32:18.820
because not many people
-- I didn't know this

00:32:18.820 --> 00:32:22.290
until I met this guy named Jim
Johnson, a wonderful professor

00:32:22.290 --> 00:32:23.650
at the University of Minnesota.

00:32:23.650 --> 00:32:26.590
And he's like, "Lance, you
need to be looking at E. Coli,

00:32:26.590 --> 00:32:29.080
because E. Coli causes all
these bladder infections."

00:32:29.080 --> 00:32:31.730
It turns out it kills
-- it causes 80

00:32:31.730 --> 00:32:34.190 position:56%
to 85 percent of bladder infections.

00:32:34.190 --> 00:32:37.730
So E. Coli is the main
neuropathogen.

00:32:37.730 --> 00:32:40.150
The gut is the immediate reservoir.

00:32:40.150 --> 00:32:44.240
So it's really E. Coli getting from
the gut into the urinary tract.

00:32:44.240 --> 00:32:47.460
I'd love to talk for a while
about how that happens,

00:32:47.460 --> 00:32:49.980
but I mean there are lots
of ways that happens.

00:32:49.980 --> 00:32:53.920
Sex is one way; the
best way, I think.

00:32:53.920 --> 00:33:00.750
So it's much better than riding a
bike with dirty underwear, I think.

00:33:00.750 --> 00:33:04.920 position:56%
[Laughter] And then so
understanding that it's the bacteria

00:33:04.920 --> 00:33:06.970
in the gut getting
into the urinary tract.

00:33:06.970 --> 00:33:09.120
And women -- I won't
ask for a show of hands,

00:33:09.120 --> 00:33:13.840
but women are at a much greater
risk for urinary tract infections,

00:33:13.840 --> 00:33:17.820
at least until we get into our 70s.

00:33:17.820 --> 00:33:20.720
So understanding how
these things then get

00:33:20.720 --> 00:33:22.640
into our guy is really important.

00:33:22.640 --> 00:33:26.640
And I, along with a number
of people, are real pioneers

00:33:26.640 --> 00:33:28.840
in this field have been asking
this question, "Is it possible

00:33:28.840 --> 00:33:30.570
that food-borne bacteria,

00:33:30.570 --> 00:33:33.150
E. Coli are causing the
urinary tract infections?"

00:33:33.150 --> 00:33:36.670
So this guy, Lee Riley, in the
middle was the first one working

00:33:36.670 --> 00:33:40.920
with Amy Mangus, on the end
there, to ask this question.

00:33:40.920 --> 00:33:43.900
They recognized these outbreaks
of urinary tract infections

00:33:43.900 --> 00:33:47.290
and they said, "This looks
like a food-borne outbreak."

00:33:47.290 --> 00:33:50.890
But they were still dancing
around this a little bit,

00:33:50.890 --> 00:33:52.420 position:56%
and it's really the genomic methods.

00:33:52.420 --> 00:33:54.470
And I'm going to tell you a
little bit about what we're doing

00:33:54.470 --> 00:33:56.400
to really resolve this issue.

00:33:56.400 --> 00:33:59.300
That's Jim Johnson
between Amy and Lee,

00:33:59.300 --> 00:34:01.340
and this is Neal Molar
[phonetic] from Denmark

00:34:01.340 --> 00:34:03.720
who also does really
wonderful work on this.

00:34:03.720 --> 00:34:06.300
And they're all friends
and collaborators.

00:34:06.300 --> 00:34:10.880
So in 2012 -- actually 2011,
I had this idea that I want

00:34:10.880 --> 00:34:15.440
to do this study to understand
this, to quantify this,

00:34:15.440 --> 00:34:18.160
and to prove whether it
does or does not happen.

00:34:18.160 --> 00:34:20.120
And so I was living in Flagstaff.

00:34:20.120 --> 00:34:23.380
That's where one of
my labs is in Arizona.

00:34:23.380 --> 00:34:26.720
And it's a small
geographically-isolated city,

00:34:26.720 --> 00:34:29.870
and we said, "Let's go
to every grocery store

00:34:29.870 --> 00:34:33.560
in the town twice per month and
buy every brand of chicken, turkey,

00:34:33.560 --> 00:34:37.030
and pork, and let's team up at
the hospital, where my friend,

00:34:37.030 --> 00:34:41.170
my good old classmate, runs
the infectious program --

00:34:41.170 --> 00:34:44.590
or the infectious disease program,
and let's collect every E. Coli

00:34:44.590 --> 00:34:47.890
from every urinary tract infection
and blood infection over the course

00:34:47.890 --> 00:34:51.690
of a year the same
year, in the same town,

00:34:51.690 --> 00:34:56.620
and let's see if we can resolve
how much overlap there is."

00:34:56.620 --> 00:34:57.990
And so we did that.

00:34:57.990 --> 00:35:01.640
And at the end of the year, we'd
sample nearly 2500 meat product,

00:35:01.640 --> 00:35:07.070
and we got almost 1300
urinary tract infections

00:35:07.070 --> 00:35:09.220
from Flagstaff Medical Center.

00:35:09.220 --> 00:35:11.420
So this is what we found
in the meat supply.

00:35:11.420 --> 00:35:13.210
It turns out most of
the meat that we tested,

00:35:13.210 --> 00:35:16.840
81% on average was
contaminated with E. Coli.

00:35:16.840 --> 00:35:20.110
No surprise, E. Coli is an
indicator of fecal contamination.

00:35:20.110 --> 00:35:23.360
You have feces in your meat.

00:35:23.360 --> 00:35:25.880
[Laughs] Sorry.

00:35:25.880 --> 00:35:27.430
Sorry, cook it, wash your hands.

00:35:27.430 --> 00:35:31.770
But nearly 90% of the
poultry products

00:35:31.770 --> 00:35:35.830
that we tested were contaminated
with E. Coli, and 60% of pork.

00:35:35.830 --> 00:35:39.700
All right; we looked at then
what were these resistant to?

00:35:39.700 --> 00:35:42.400
They were resistant to lots
of different antibiotics.

00:35:42.400 --> 00:35:46.100
And so the blue line, the
blue column is from chicken.

00:35:46.100 --> 00:35:47.590
So this are the E.
Coli from chicken.

00:35:47.590 --> 00:35:50.930
Each of these three-letter
codes is a different antibiotic.

00:35:50.930 --> 00:35:53.950
And the percent is the percent
of the E. Coli that we tested

00:35:53.950 --> 00:35:56.250
that was resistant to these
different antibiotics.

00:35:56.250 --> 00:36:01.510
And what you see, you will notice
that turkey is off-scale, right?

00:36:01.510 --> 00:36:02.810
Why is that?

00:36:02.810 --> 00:36:04.680
Well, I would guess that it's

00:36:04.680 --> 00:36:06.190
because they're using
more antibiotics

00:36:06.190 --> 00:36:08.360
than these other commodity
producers.

00:36:08.360 --> 00:36:10.230
But in the United States,
we don't have the right

00:36:10.230 --> 00:36:13.560
to know what antibiotics are
being used in which animals,

00:36:13.560 --> 00:36:15.510
because that's a trade secret.

00:36:15.510 --> 00:36:18.610
Antibiotic use in animal
production is a secret.

00:36:18.610 --> 00:36:21.200
It's their secret for making
cheap meat for you guys.

00:36:21.200 --> 00:36:23.370
Now, don't have that sour look.

00:36:23.370 --> 00:36:26.480 position:56%
The one place where gentamicin is --

00:36:26.480 --> 00:36:30.810
the one place where chicken beats
turkey is actually gentamicin.

00:36:30.810 --> 00:36:34.890
And that's because it's legal to
inject chicken eggs with gentamicin

00:36:34.890 --> 00:36:39.260
in the United States, to prevent
infections from possibly occurring.

00:36:39.260 --> 00:36:44.040
So we have these machines, we have
machines that injects pallets full

00:36:44.040 --> 00:36:47.890
of eggs simultaneously while
we're also administering vaccines.

00:36:47.890 --> 00:36:50.220
Vaccines, I love; I
think that's a good idea.

00:36:50.220 --> 00:36:53.470
Injecting antibiotics
into eggs, terrible idea.

00:36:53.470 --> 00:36:56.320
And we did a study of people
who catch chickens for a living

00:36:56.320 --> 00:36:57.830
and they had 32 times the risk

00:36:57.830 --> 00:37:02.840
of carrying gentamicin resistant
E. Coli as their community peers.

00:37:02.840 --> 00:37:04.970
So now we're asking are
these bacteria related?

00:37:04.970 --> 00:37:10.620
So we have 1900 -- or nearly
2,000 E. Coli from the meat.

00:37:10.620 --> 00:37:14.490 position:56%
So 81% of all those products that we
tested, we got E. Coli from there.

00:37:14.490 --> 00:37:17.500
And then we have E. Coli from
urine and blood in the hospital.

00:37:17.500 --> 00:37:18.800
And now what are we going to do,

00:37:18.800 --> 00:37:20.100
we're going to sequence
all those genomes.

00:37:20.100 --> 00:37:21.470
I told you it got really
cheap, right?

00:37:21.470 --> 00:37:25.550
And we have a million dollar grant.

00:37:25.550 --> 00:37:26.850
We spent it in two years.

00:37:26.850 --> 00:37:29.070
We had a million dollar
grant to do this.

00:37:29.070 --> 00:37:32.610
And so we sequenced all
of those genomes using one

00:37:32.610 --> 00:37:34.810 position:56%
of these next generation sequencers.

00:37:34.810 --> 00:37:36.110
So we have a three-step approach.

00:37:36.110 --> 00:37:41.270
And this is kind of wonky, so
just roll with me for a minute.

00:37:41.270 --> 00:37:43.980
I'll boil it back down
with Fisher-Price,

00:37:43.980 --> 00:37:46.890
or I'll at least try
to be simple about it.

00:37:46.890 --> 00:37:48.920
So what we do is we
sequence the genomes,

00:37:48.920 --> 00:37:53.700
and then we do a low-resolution
genotype,

00:37:53.700 --> 00:37:57.410
so using a standard method called
multi-locus sequence typing.

00:37:57.410 --> 00:37:58.710
Doesn't matter.

00:37:58.710 --> 00:38:01.710
But we assign them to a sequence
type so we can group them together.

00:38:01.710 --> 00:38:04.550
And then we use the whole
genome to understand

00:38:04.550 --> 00:38:07.550
to make one of those family trees.

00:38:07.550 --> 00:38:10.300
If we try to do them altogether,
we lose resolution actually,

00:38:10.300 --> 00:38:11.600
so this is the way that we do it.

00:38:11.600 --> 00:38:13.800
We group them, then
we make a family tree.

00:38:13.800 --> 00:38:15.510
We group them, we make
a family tree.

00:38:15.510 --> 00:38:17.410 position:56%
And we ask at a very high resolution

00:38:17.410 --> 00:38:19.540
with the best resolution
you could ever hope

00:38:19.540 --> 00:38:22.620
to have using the whole genome
sequence, "How are these related

00:38:22.620 --> 00:38:25.370
to one another, what we see in the
food and what we see in the people

00:38:25.370 --> 00:38:29.180
in the same city, over the
same course of the year?"

00:38:29.180 --> 00:38:31.520
Okay; so here's the first thing.

