00:42:24.630 --> 00:42:27.770
of the urinary tract infections
in Flagstaff, Arizona --

00:42:27.770 --> 00:42:31.570
and Flagstaff, Arizona is very
representative of the rest

00:42:31.570 --> 00:42:35.650
of the country, because all the
meat that we produce is produced

00:42:35.650 --> 00:42:39.470
in these local areas and then
distributed throughout the country.

00:42:39.470 --> 00:42:41.930
So nine percent is our
very conservative estimate,

00:42:41.930 --> 00:42:45.790
and it may be as high as 12-plus.

00:42:45.790 --> 00:42:52.410
When we loosen up our -- yes when
we loosen it up, it's 12-plus.

00:42:52.410 --> 00:42:55.100
So we're talking about -- now
if you scale that to the rest

00:42:55.100 --> 00:42:58.340
of the country, we're talking about
over half a million infections --

00:42:58.340 --> 00:43:02.470
at our -- at the most conservative
estimate, half a million

00:43:02.470 --> 00:43:07.370
to 700,000 infections that we
had no idea were food borne.

00:43:07.370 --> 00:43:11.420
So this represents a
totally different paradigm,

00:43:11.420 --> 00:43:14.690
and a new conduit for
resistance genes from --

00:43:14.690 --> 00:43:16.180
a newly-recognized conduit

00:43:16.180 --> 00:43:18.970
of resistance genes
from animals to people.

00:43:18.970 --> 00:43:22.050
And I can tell you, the other
thing that we haven't even looked

00:43:22.050 --> 00:43:24.410
at is the resistance genes
moving independently,

00:43:24.410 --> 00:43:27.040
which is another thing
we have to look at.

00:43:27.040 --> 00:43:32.570
So I just want to stop here
for a second, and, you know,

00:43:32.570 --> 00:43:33.870
I always see confusion when I talk

00:43:33.870 --> 00:43:35.730
about food-borne urinary
tract infections.

00:43:35.730 --> 00:43:38.340
So what happens is that
you mishandle the poultry,

00:43:38.340 --> 00:43:41.570
or you consume undercooked
poultry or some other meat,

00:43:41.570 --> 00:43:44.900 position:56%
and you consume the E. Coli, it
gets in your gut, and it grows there

00:43:44.900 --> 00:43:47.770
for a little while and then it
makes the short trip from --

00:43:47.770 --> 00:43:50.190
sorry to be graphic, from
your anus to your urethra,

00:43:50.190 --> 00:43:53.540
and you have a bladder
infection from food.

00:43:53.540 --> 00:43:58.020
Okay; does that make sense?

00:43:58.020 --> 00:44:01.120
So we coin this term "food-borne
urinary tract infections."

00:44:01.120 --> 00:44:05.110
I like to call them "foodies,"
foodies against foodies.

00:44:05.110 --> 00:44:08.680
And this is truly a paradigm
shift in what is a food borne,

00:44:08.680 --> 00:44:10.420
or a food-associated infection.

00:44:10.420 --> 00:44:14.260
Right; it's no longer --
sorry I'm a microbiologist;

00:44:14.260 --> 00:44:16.410
it's no longer diarrhea
and vomiting, right?

00:44:16.410 --> 00:44:22.230 position:56%
Now it can be MRSA infection, it can
be an untreatable bladder infection.

00:44:22.230 --> 00:44:26.530
And it gives us new context
for those 34 million pounds

00:44:26.530 --> 00:44:29.950
of antibiotics that we use in
the United States each year.

00:44:29.950 --> 00:44:34.960
But we are not alone, right, and
we've distributed this model,

00:44:34.960 --> 00:44:38.740 position:56%
we've shown this model of industrial
animal production to the world.

00:44:38.740 --> 00:44:43.710
And the world is changing
their consumption habits.

00:44:43.710 --> 00:44:48.000 position:56%
So the BRICS nations, Brazil,
Russian, India, China, South Africa,

00:44:48.000 --> 00:44:50.010
these countries are
developing very quickly,

00:44:50.010 --> 00:44:52.430
and they're adopting
our meat-centric diet,

00:44:52.430 --> 00:44:54.940
and they're adopting our
methods of producing animals

00:44:54.940 --> 00:44:57.990 position:56%
in these industrialized system
using lots of different antibiotics.

00:44:57.990 --> 00:45:00.580
And this is a global challenge
that we all have to meet.

00:45:00.580 --> 00:45:05.180
And the problem is that we
don't have a box to stand on,

00:45:05.180 --> 00:45:06.480
because we've been doing it.

00:45:06.480 --> 00:45:07.950
We designed the system,

00:45:07.950 --> 00:45:13.060
and we really haven't
changed much over the years.

00:45:13.060 --> 00:45:17.320
And my birthday is November 19th; I
don't know if you can see the date,

00:45:17.320 --> 00:45:20.670
but November 19th this
hit the media cycle.

00:45:20.670 --> 00:45:25.810
So new mobile resistance element
was found in animals and people.

00:45:25.810 --> 00:45:29.000
So it turns out that China
had adopted our methods

00:45:29.000 --> 00:45:31.520
of using antibiotics in
food animal production.

00:45:31.520 --> 00:45:35.090
They were using our last
drug, a drug called Colastin,

00:45:35.090 --> 00:45:37.280
our last drug for treating CRE,

00:45:37.280 --> 00:45:39.710
carbapenem-resistant
enterobacteriaceae,

00:45:39.710 --> 00:45:42.220
that's super E. Coli,
super-resistant E. Coli

00:45:42.220 --> 00:45:45.070
and its cousins to
klebsiella and those guys.

00:45:45.070 --> 00:45:49.750
They were using that drug to
raise animals using our model;

00:45:49.750 --> 00:45:54.180
because it was an old drug,
nobody cared about it until we ran

00:45:54.180 --> 00:45:57.660
out of drugs and we got desperate
and we started using colistin.

00:45:57.660 --> 00:45:59.960
And then all of the sudden,

00:45:59.960 --> 00:46:02.770
we realized that this
new gene had evolved.

00:46:02.770 --> 00:46:04.070
We'd never seen it before.

00:46:04.070 --> 00:46:06.080
It was a mobile piece of DNA,

00:46:06.080 --> 00:46:08.830
a piece of DNA that's
very readily transmissible

00:46:08.830 --> 00:46:11.730
between different strains
of E. Coli and klebsiella.

00:46:11.730 --> 00:46:17.290
And so this just hit my
field like a ton of bricks.

00:46:17.290 --> 00:46:22.310
And in the weeks that
followed, we had my colleagues

00:46:22.310 --> 00:46:25.110
around the world started
scanning their databases of DNA

00:46:25.110 --> 00:46:28.490 position:56%
and I said, "Hey, it's here already.

00:46:28.490 --> 00:46:29.790
Hey, it's over here already."

00:46:29.790 --> 00:46:32.220
The highest concentration
that we've seen is in China

00:46:32.220 --> 00:46:33.550
where they were doing this.

00:46:33.550 --> 00:46:36.920
But we found it now it's already
in the United States as well.

00:46:36.920 --> 00:46:40.740
And that's that last -- this is
the last card for that royal flush.

00:46:40.740 --> 00:46:46.530
So for CRE, some strains of
CRE are just missing one gene,

00:46:46.530 --> 00:46:49.150
