00:46:49.150 --> 00:46:55.870
And so now we're talking about
untreatable bacteria on meat.

00:46:55.870 --> 00:46:58.300
But we don't even recognize
this kind

00:46:58.300 --> 00:47:00.860
of E. Coli is food-borne pathogens.

00:47:00.860 --> 00:47:02.160
So how do we regulate that?

00:47:02.160 --> 00:47:05.500
How do we say we don't
want your product?

00:47:05.500 --> 00:47:08.370
And how do we respond to
China and other countries

00:47:08.370 --> 00:47:11.860
that are using our last drugs
for food animal production,

00:47:11.860 --> 00:47:16.200
or any drugs, you know, in an
abusive fashion, how do we respond

00:47:16.200 --> 00:47:18.590
to them when we do the same
thing in the United States?

00:47:18.590 --> 00:47:21.070
It's really difficult.

00:47:21.070 --> 00:47:22.910
So I'm just wrapping up.

00:47:22.910 --> 00:47:28.750
I just have a couple of final
thoughts, and then we can talk.

00:47:28.750 --> 00:47:33.140
The flyer said, "Antibiotics,
good or bad?"

00:47:33.140 --> 00:47:34.620
Antibiotics, good.

00:47:34.620 --> 00:47:37.430
I mean, antibiotics have
saved countless lives

00:47:37.430 --> 00:47:38.730
since their discovery,

00:47:38.730 --> 00:47:43.480 position:56%
since Alexander Fleming accidentally
discovered penicillin in the 1930s,

00:47:43.480 --> 00:47:45.320
and they were introduced
to human medicine.

00:47:45.320 --> 00:47:49.850
Yes; they have a profound effect
on our microbiome, that is,

00:47:49.850 --> 00:47:51.150
the community of bacteria

00:47:51.150 --> 00:47:54.340
that we actually are,
you know, dependent on.

00:47:54.340 --> 00:48:00.370 position:56%
But our microbiomes generally
recover from those temporary things,

00:48:00.370 --> 00:48:05.040
and these antibiotics save us from
the immediate, the acute infection

00:48:05.040 --> 00:48:06.410
that we're suffering from.

00:48:06.410 --> 00:48:07.870
Someday we might have
something better

00:48:07.870 --> 00:48:10.330
that specifically kills
just the bad bacteria

00:48:10.330 --> 00:48:13.060
and leaves the good bacteria
intact, and those are some

00:48:13.060 --> 00:48:15.330
of the things we're
trying to work on at GW.

00:48:15.330 --> 00:48:21.210
But for now, this is the
best thing that we have,

00:48:21.210 --> 00:48:23.010
and we should really protect them.

00:48:23.010 --> 00:48:25.290
And then the other
thing I want to say is

00:48:25.290 --> 00:48:26.710
that sick animals need antibiotics.

00:48:26.710 --> 00:48:28.850
So I don't want anybody to walk out
of here thinking that I'm saying

00:48:28.850 --> 00:48:30.850
that we shouldn't treat sick
animals with antibiotics.

00:48:30.850 --> 00:48:32.450
We should.

00:48:32.450 --> 00:48:37.120
But if we have a system that
makes animals sick by design,

00:48:37.120 --> 00:48:39.770
that system's broken and we
have to change that system.

00:48:39.770 --> 00:48:43.050
And we may not have to go
to something as radical

00:48:43.050 --> 00:48:47.920
as free-ranging happy little pigs,
but we should be raising them

00:48:47.920 --> 00:48:50.180
in a way that doesn't
make them sick repeatedly.

00:48:50.180 --> 00:48:53.010
I mean, if you can predict it
based on a clock or a calendar

00:48:53.010 --> 00:48:55.220
that they're going to get sick
and you have to have antibiotics,

00:48:55.220 --> 00:48:57.680 position:56%
that system's broken, in my opinion.

00:48:57.680 --> 00:49:02.740
And the last thing I want to
end with is a message of hope.

00:49:02.740 --> 00:49:08.010
I don't think that the
post-antibiotic era is inevitable.

00:49:08.010 --> 00:49:10.480
I mean, some people
have already reached it,

00:49:10.480 --> 00:49:12.920
23,000 Americans die
each year, right,

00:49:12.920 --> 00:49:16.410
but this time when
there's just no antibiotics

00:49:16.410 --> 00:49:18.640
at work, that's not inevitable.

00:49:18.640 --> 00:49:21.390
I just came back from Scandinavia.

