00:51:43.350 --> 00:51:47.920 position:56%
I mean, it's not a perfect science
yet, like how long do you take them,

00:51:47.920 --> 00:51:50.080
and how much do you take?

00:51:50.080 --> 00:51:53.770
Right; so it's really adjusted for
body mass size, and you've noticed

00:51:53.770 --> 00:51:57.750
in the United States that body
masses are changing, right?

00:51:57.750 --> 00:52:03.220 position:56%
And but what we're learning is that
-- or what some drugs we're learning

00:52:03.220 --> 00:52:08.000
that you can cut back the amount
of time that people are on,

00:52:08.000 --> 00:52:11.760
so that you reduce that pressure
on all the bacteria in the person.

00:52:11.760 --> 00:52:13.630
Right; so you can dial that back.

00:52:13.630 --> 00:52:16.300
But you should do it for -- you
should take them for as long

00:52:16.300 --> 00:52:19.550
as the doctor says you should
take them, and let them figure

00:52:19.550 --> 00:52:21.280
out what that time should be.

00:52:21.280 --> 00:52:24.260
But right now, you know, if they
say ten days, take it for ten days;

00:52:24.260 --> 00:52:26.170
if they say three days,
take it for three days.

00:52:26.170 --> 00:52:27.620
Did I answer your question?

00:52:27.620 --> 00:52:30.850
&gt;&gt; Right. I just think maybe
it's not optimized in regards

00:52:31.910 --> 00:52:41.190
to being treated ended up
unnecessarily so that overdose

00:52:41.190 --> 00:52:43.550
of any kind actually helped
to, you know, [inaudible].

00:52:43.550 --> 00:52:45.510
&gt;&gt; Lance Price: Right;
so I agree both dosing

00:52:45.510 --> 00:52:47.970
and who gets antibiotics
is not optimized.

00:52:47.970 --> 00:52:50.090
Right; so people are --

00:52:50.090 --> 00:52:53.690
doctors often prescribe what
we called "empirically," right?

00:52:53.690 --> 00:52:56.690
So somebody comes in and they
have some symptoms that could be

00:52:56.690 --> 00:52:59.500 position:56%
or could not be bacterial
infections, but they don't have time

00:52:59.500 --> 00:53:01.960
to like collect the culture,
and wait for the culture,

00:53:01.960 --> 00:53:04.680
or they don't think they have time
to do this, collect the culture,

00:53:04.680 --> 00:53:06.840
wait for the culture to come
back, check those records,

00:53:06.840 --> 00:53:11.670
and then make a reactive
recommendation.

00:53:11.670 --> 00:53:15.070
And so they just guess and they
say, "Ah, you probably have E. Coli

00:53:15.070 --> 00:53:18.140
in your bladder, and it's
probably susceptible to this.

00:53:18.140 --> 00:53:19.440
Here's a prescription.

00:53:19.440 --> 00:53:20.740
Get out of here."

00:53:20.740 --> 00:53:23.790
And so what we really want to do
is move towards a rapid molecular

00:53:23.790 --> 00:53:29.230
diagnostics so they can
collect the pee in the office,

00:53:29.230 --> 00:53:33.140
and within 15 minutes know
exactly what you're infected with,

00:53:33.140 --> 00:53:35.870
what it's susceptible to, and
give you the exact antibiotics

00:53:35.870 --> 00:53:38.020
that you should have
for the exact duration.

00:53:38.020 --> 00:53:40.860
And I think we'll be there
in a few years, actually.

00:53:40.860 --> 00:53:44.760
Yes. I mean, the molecular
techniques are out there.

00:53:44.760 --> 00:53:53.530
Yes. You had a question back there.

00:53:53.530 --> 00:53:54.830
Yes?

00:53:54.830 --> 00:53:59.390
&gt;&gt; Yes; [inaudible] so
what is your recommendation

00:53:59.390 --> 00:54:02.100
for staying clear of [inaudible] --

00:54:02.100 --> 00:54:04.460
&gt;&gt; Lance Price: What should you
do; is that what you're -- [laughs]

00:54:04.460 --> 00:54:09.140
&gt;&gt; Yes; should we go organic,
should we give up eating?

00:54:09.140 --> 00:54:11.300
I mean, what is your [inaudible]?

00:54:11.300 --> 00:54:12.600
&gt;&gt; Lance Price: So I'd
be a hypocrite to say

00:54:12.600 --> 00:54:15.280
that you should give up meat,
although it is a healthy choice.

00:54:15.280 --> 00:54:17.870
I'm not a vegan or a vegetarian.

00:54:17.870 --> 00:54:23.370
But that is one way to avoid food
borne drug-resistant bacteria.

00:54:23.370 --> 00:54:25.930 position:56%
The other part of this, though, is
that nine billion animals make a lot

00:54:25.930 --> 00:54:29.430
of poop, and that poop is
used as fertilizer on crops

00:54:29.430 --> 00:54:33.200
where they grow vegetables
that vegetarians eat.

00:54:33.200 --> 00:54:34.890
Right; so this is an
ecological problem.

00:54:34.890 --> 00:54:39.760
So we don't -- you know, consumer
choice helps, but we really --

00:54:39.760 --> 00:54:43.980
you know, we need to tackle
this as a global community.

00:54:43.980 --> 00:54:48.340
But yes so what I do is
personally is I only buy products

00:54:48.340 --> 00:54:51.020
that are raised from animals
raised with that antibiotic,

00:54:51.020 --> 00:54:52.320
so I look for that label.

00:54:52.320 --> 00:54:54.040
That's the only label
that really matters there.

00:54:54.040 --> 00:54:56.240
Or organic is also a
label that indicates

00:54:56.240 --> 00:54:58.850
that they have not been
treated with antibiotics.

00:54:58.850 --> 00:55:02.360
And then there's a new label that's
coming out that's responsibly used.

00:55:02.360 --> 00:55:10.240
What's the actual term -- anyway
there's a responsible use term

00:55:10.240 --> 00:55:14.070
that they're working on
now, and that has to be --

00:55:14.070 --> 00:55:17.670
we're really pushing for that
to be only third-party verified.

00:55:17.670 --> 00:55:20.560
So it has the be the USDA verifying

00:55:20.560 --> 00:55:22.770
that they're actually
using them responsibly,

00:55:22.770 --> 00:55:25.040
which would only be
to treat sick animals.

00:55:25.040 --> 00:55:28.660 position:56%
And so we need -- I'm really leery
of this, but I do think that we need

00:55:28.660 --> 00:55:32.440
to get there eventually is allowing
for the treatment of sick animals

00:55:32.440 --> 00:55:36.140
and still selling that, you
know, with a specific label.

00:55:36.140 --> 00:55:38.010
But it has to be third-party
verified.

00:55:38.010 --> 00:55:41.960
We can't count on companies
to make that designation.

00:55:41.960 --> 00:55:44.240 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Right; I was told that organic --
there are certain levels of organic,

00:55:44.240 --> 00:55:45.540
so they still use antibiotics,

00:55:45.540 --> 00:55:51.960
or some type of hormones,
just not as many.

00:55:51.960 --> 00:55:55.200
&gt;&gt; Lance Price: Not with organic;
organics is a very tight label.

00:55:55.200 --> 00:55:59.300
That's a meaning -- natural
is just complete garbage.

00:55:59.300 --> 00:56:02.220
So natural is the one
you're probably thinking of.

00:56:02.220 --> 00:56:04.390
That just means there's no
plastic in there, you know?

00:56:04.390 --> 00:56:07.850 position:56%
[Laughter] You know, I mean, so yes.

00:56:07.850 --> 00:56:09.180
Yes, and then -- yes.

00:56:09.180 --> 00:56:11.910
&gt;&gt; Is there any significant
legislation

00:56:11.910 --> 00:56:14.190
from [inaudible] try to
address these issues?

00:56:14.190 --> 00:56:16.920
And if you were to impose new
legislation today to [inaudible],

00:56:16.920 --> 00:56:19.610
what would be the key [inaudible]?

00:56:19.610 --> 00:56:23.310 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Lance Price: Right; Louise
Slaughter is our only microbiologist

00:56:23.310 --> 00:56:28.050
in Congress, and she has
repeatedly put forth legislation

00:56:28.050 --> 00:56:34.580
to reduce antibiotic use in animal
production to only therapeutic use,

00:56:34.580 --> 00:56:37.780
and bring all antibiotic use
under control of the veterinarian.

00:56:37.780 --> 00:56:44.930
And that has been received
almost as if you were proposing

00:56:44.930 --> 00:56:52.110 position:56%
to require all schoolboy -- all
male children in school wear skirts.

00:56:52.110 --> 00:56:57.090 position:56%
It's somehow just super-radical that
you would only allow antibiotics

00:56:57.090 --> 00:56:58.670
to be used for sick animals.

00:56:58.670 --> 00:57:03.440
So Louise Slaughter's bill,
it never gets voted on.

00:57:03.440 --> 00:57:07.690
But that -- it's a great bill,
PAMTA, Preservation of Antibiotics

00:57:07.690 --> 00:57:09.500
for Medical Treatment Act.

00:57:09.500 --> 00:57:13.040
And I can't remember the
name of the Senate side bill.

00:57:13.040 --> 00:57:19.570
But I think with more and
more companies coming onboard

00:57:19.570 --> 00:57:24.250 position:56%
with saying -- you know, like, big
companies like McDonald's and Tyson,

00:57:24.250 --> 00:57:27.100
and big producers saying,
"Hey, we're going to get rid

00:57:27.100 --> 00:57:29.390 position:56%
of non-therapeutic biotics, at least

00:57:29.390 --> 00:57:32.180
in poultry" it makes
it a safer environments

00:57:32.180 --> 00:57:35.000
for Congress to kind of step in.

00:57:35.000 --> 00:57:40.240 position:56%
And so we're hoping that a bill like
that might gain momentum someday,

00:57:40.240 --> 00:57:42.010
and God Bless Louise Slaughter.

00:57:42.010 --> 00:57:43.600
[ Inaudible Comment ]

00:57:43.600 --> 00:57:44.900
What's that?

00:57:44.900 --> 00:57:46.200
&gt;&gt; What was the name,
one more time, PAMTA?

00:57:46.200 --> 00:57:48.180
&gt;&gt; Lance Price: PAMTA,
Preservation of Antibiotics

00:57:48.180 --> 00:57:50.350
for Medical Treatment Act.

00:57:50.350 --> 00:57:51.890
And I really like that.

00:57:51.890 --> 00:57:54.180
There's also star legislation --

00:57:54.180 --> 00:57:56.950
I don't know if that one's
still getting introduced,

00:57:56.950 --> 00:57:59.910
but that was something that Stuart
Levy was a real champion of,

00:57:59.910 --> 00:58:02.800
which is just real
monitoring of antibiotics

00:58:02.800 --> 00:58:04.100
and antibiotic resistance.

00:58:04.100 --> 00:58:06.220
And that's one of the things
that we need, we need data.

00:58:06.220 --> 00:58:07.520
I mean, it's ridiculous

00:58:07.520 --> 00:58:10.500
that antibiotic use can be
considered a trade secret.

00:58:10.500 --> 00:58:14.170
It is a shared resource that
needs to be productive by all

00:58:14.170 --> 00:58:17.190
of us, and it's just a shame.

00:58:17.190 --> 00:58:18.490
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

00:58:18.490 --> 00:58:19.790
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

00:58:19.790 --> 00:58:23.060
And FDA has done some
things, but not enough.

00:58:23.060 --> 00:58:30.420
&gt;&gt; I heard that the bacteria
in pork is very hard to kill.

00:58:30.420 --> 00:58:38.960 position:56%
Even if you cook the pork well done,
the bacteria is still not killed.

00:58:38.960 --> 00:58:42.960
I mean, that is -- I
heard from [inaudible],

00:58:42.960 --> 00:58:47.800
and she said that's
why we don't eat pork,

00:58:47.800 --> 00:58:52.120
[laughter] because it's still the
same, and I heard it from somebody

00:58:52.120 --> 00:58:55.290 position:56%
who is doing research, and I ate it.

00:58:55.290 --> 00:58:57.900
So I don't know whether
that is true.

00:58:57.900 --> 00:59:02.210
To me, bacteria is
bacteria, and you kill them

00:59:02.210 --> 00:59:05.710
at the same temperature
wherever they are, right?

00:59:05.710 --> 00:59:07.930
&gt;&gt; Lance Price: Yes; there can
be a little bit of variation

00:59:07.930 --> 00:59:11.670
in thermo-stability,
but I'm with you.

00:59:11.670 --> 00:59:13.690
Most it is very killable
with cooking

00:59:13.690 --> 00:59:19.110
and a well-done pork chop
is not a risk factor.

00:59:19.110 --> 00:59:21.800
It's handling that raw pork chop
that you bring into your house.

00:59:21.800 --> 00:59:23.890
And there used to be
something called "trichinosis,"

00:59:23.890 --> 00:59:29.420
and there still is trichinosis that
you can get from undercooked pork.

00:59:29.420 --> 00:59:31.640
But in the United States,
it's largely absent

00:59:31.640 --> 00:59:34.750
from our pork production, and
that's not even a bacteria,

00:59:34.750 --> 00:59:36.310
and that's a parasite.

00:59:36.310 --> 00:59:44.070 position:56%
So we've seen some -- there are some
strains of E. Coli, for instance,

00:59:44.070 --> 00:59:45.950
that are a little more heat-stable,

00:59:45.950 --> 00:59:48.780
but nothing that could put
up with a good grilling.

00:59:48.780 --> 00:59:51.510 position:56%
Yes. Do I need to shut up or -- yes.

00:59:51.510 --> 00:59:54.550
[ Inaudible Comment ]

00:59:54.550 --> 00:59:56.860
&gt;&gt; I've got a question
regarding like hand washing

00:59:56.860 --> 01:00:00.490
and antibacterial soap,
wasn't that recently sort

01:00:00.490 --> 01:00:04.260
of [inaudible] scaling
back the use of it?

01:00:04.260 --> 01:00:05.560
&gt;&gt; Lance Price: Right.

01:00:05.560 --> 01:00:09.560
&gt;&gt; How does that kind
of affect [inaudible] --

01:00:09.560 --> 01:00:11.840
&gt;&gt; Lance Price: Yes; so there's
something called "triclosan,"

01:00:11.840 --> 01:00:13.880
and "triclocarban" that
they put into soaps.

01:00:13.880 --> 01:00:16.540
These are antimicrobials
that they put into soaps.

01:00:16.540 --> 01:00:19.740
And, you know, it never
really -- it was never --

01:00:19.740 --> 01:00:23.610
triclosan soaps were never really
any better than regular soap.

01:00:23.610 --> 01:00:26.670
I mean, it's the physical
action in these little bubbles

01:00:26.670 --> 01:00:29.360
that actually take the
bacteria off your hands

01:00:29.360 --> 01:00:31.000 position:56%
and flush them down the sink, right?

01:00:31.000 --> 01:00:36.490
And but the problem is that those
drugs can in the environment select

01:00:36.490 --> 01:00:37.790
for drug-resistant bacteria.

01:00:37.790 --> 01:00:41.510
But they can also produce these
stable toxic compounds that look

01:00:41.510 --> 01:00:44.490
like dioxin in the environment.

01:00:44.490 --> 01:00:48.360
And so it was never a good idea,
it was just always a sales gimmick.

01:00:48.360 --> 01:00:53.160
And so I understand that
they're trying to ban that now,

01:00:53.160 --> 01:00:55.410
and it couldn't be sooner.

01:00:55.410 --> 01:00:56.860
Yes.

